      "content": "Scientists have conducted numerous experiments to test the phenomenon of quantum entanglement and to rule out the possibility of hidden variables. One of the most famous experiments is the Bell test experiment, named after physicist John Bell, who proposed a theoretical framework to test the existence of entanglement.\n\nIn a Bell test experiment, pairs of entangled particles are sent to two distant locations, and their properties (like spin or polarization) are measured. The measurements are performed using random settings, so the results are not predetermined. According to local realism, a theory that assumes that the properties of particles are determined by hidden variables and that information cannot travel faster than light, the results of these measurements should satisfy certain inequalities, known as Bell inequalities.\n\nHowever, numerous experiments have shown that the results of entangled particle measurements violate these Bell inequalities, suggesting that the properties of the particles are not determined by hidden variables but are instead instantaneously correlated, regardless of the distance between them.\n\nThese experiments have been conducted with increasing precision and over larger distances, further confirming the existence of quantum entanglement and ruling out the possibility of hidden variables. While the exact mechanism behind entanglement is still not fully understood, the experimental evidence strongly supports the idea that entanglement is a fundamental",
